    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-11-18T17:50:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-11-18T17:50:00-05:00" n="162"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d162">
                <head>162. Transcript of Telephone Conversation Between the President’s Assistant
                    for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from"
                        >Kissinger</persName>) and Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_LMR2"
                        type="to">Laird</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d162fn1">Source: Library of Congress,
                        Manuscript Division, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>
                        Papers, Box 361, Telephone Conversations, Chronological File, November
                        18–28, 1969. No classification marking.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d162fn2">The conversation dealt with
                        follow-up to the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> meeting and the
                        possible draft of a legislative strategy to address the <gloss
                            target="#t_CBW1">CBW</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1969-11-18T17:50:00-05:00">November 18, 1969, 5:50 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>[Omitted here is unrelated material.]</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said on the <gloss target="#t_CBW1">CBW</gloss>
                    thing … L said don’t call it <gloss target="#t_CBW1">CBW</gloss>, that’s what
                    the opponents call it. <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said anyway, he would run
                    that guidance past <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss>. <gloss target="#t_K1"
                        >K</gloss> wanted to make sure it’s what <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss> had
                    in mind. <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> asked <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss>
                    if he could send over some legislative strategy. <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss>
                    said the problem is this has never been done—<gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss> has
                    been working on this for 16 years, and they’ve never been able to get anybody to
                    address himself to this. <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss> said this would be
                    useful—it’s important to develop a few positions down the line like this. <gloss
                        target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said he would send over a draft. <gloss
                        target="#t_L1">L</gloss> said both on public affairs and legislative side.
                    Then we can issue instructions, and <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss> thinks we
                    can keep everybody quiet until this thing comes out. <gloss target="#t_L1"
                        >L</gloss> said they would try to get it released this weekend.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> asked if L went along with the Geneva protocol
                    thing; <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss> said yes, but we shouldn’t get tear gas
                    mixed up with the protocol thing. <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said he would
                    make sure in the <gloss target="#t_NSDM1">NSDM</gloss> to leave no doubt about
                    the President’s feeling about that. <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> asked if
                        <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss> had noticed what <gloss target="#t_K1"
                        >K</gloss> put out yesterday on <gloss target="#t_ABM1">ABM</gloss>. <gloss
                        target="#t_L1">L</gloss> said yes, very good.</p>
            </div>
